            <div class="section-inner">
              <div class="hack-item">
                <div class="hack-num">1</div>
                <div>
                  <p><strong>Potato in exhaust pipe to stall engine.</strong> MacGyver stuffs a potato into a vehicle's exhaust pipe to disable the engine.</p>
                  <span class="hack-verdict pass">CONFIRMED</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="science-block">
                <h4>Exhaust Backpressure and Engine Stalling</h4>
                <p>A potato blocks the exhaust pipe, preventing hot gases from escaping. This creates backpressure that disrupts the engine's four-stroke cycle, causing misfiring, surging, and eventual stalling. The engine starves for air as the blockage prevents the exhaust valve from clearing. This is a real sabotage technique—simple, effective, and reversible.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="hack-item">
                <div class="hack-num">2</div>
                <div>
                  <p><strong>Blankets + gas cans to jam speedboat water intake.</strong> MacGyver uses blankets and fuel containers to clog a speedboat's cooling water intake, disabling the engine.</p>
                  <span class="hack-verdict pass">CONFIRMED</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="science-block">
                <h4>Cooling System Blockage and Engine Overheating</h4>
                <p>Marine engines rely on continuous water circulation for cooling. A blanket or debris wedged into the intake prevents water flow. Without cooling, the engine temperature rises rapidly, seizuring the engine and potentially causing fire. This is a legitimate sabotage technique. Bilge strainers exist precisely because this vulnerability is well-known.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="hack-item">
                <div class="hack-num">3</div>
                <div>
                  <p><strong>Lightbulb tungsten filament as lock pick.</strong> MacGyver removes the tungsten filament from a lightbulb to use as a precision lock-picking tool.</p>
                  <span class="hack-verdict pass">CONFIRMED</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="science-block">
                <h4>Lock Picking and Material Properties</h4>
                <p>Tungsten filaments are thin, rigid, and resistant to deformation. A straightened filament can manipulate pin-tumbler locks. Lock picking is a recognized skill; the specific tool geometry matters less than the ability to feel pins setting. Tungsten's durability makes it suitable for precision manipulation. Real locksmiths have improvised with similar materials.</p>
              </div>

              <div class="hack-item">
                <div class="hack-num">4</div>
                <div>
                  <p><strong>Caulking compound adhesive for repairs.</strong> MacGyver uses caulking material to seal or bond components together in an emergency repair.</p>
                  <span class="hack-verdict plausible">PLAUSIBLE</span>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="science-block">
                <h4>Polymerization and Adhesive Bonding</h4>
                <p>Caulking compounds are typically polyurethane or silicone-based polymers that cure through moisture or chemical polymerization. Once set, they form a rigid bond. For temporary repairs, caulking can seal gaps or hold components. The bond strength is moderate, not suitable for high-stress applications, but adequate for short-term field fixes.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
